## 6. State & Data Flow

### End-to-End Flow Through Module H

```
[Browser] → WebSocket → [Node.js Express handler]
                              │
                              │  grpcClient.runCalibration(req)   ← constructed from WS message
                              ▼
                        [gRPC channel → localhost:50051]
                              │
                              ▼
                        [Python PhysicsCaptureServicer.RunCalibration]
                              │
                              │  yield CalibrationStatus  (per camera, per stage)
                              ▼
                        [gRPC stream back to Node.js]
                              │
                              │  for await (status of calibrationStream)
                              ▼
                        [Node.js WebSocket relay]
                              │
                              ▼
                        [Browser WebSocket] → Zustand store → React progress UI
```

### Intermediate Representations

| Stage                   | Representation                                     |
| ----------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| gRPC message on wire    | Protobuf binary (framed with 5-byte length prefix) |
| In Node.js after decode | Plain JS object matching TypeScript interface      |
| Forwarded to browser    | JSON string (WebSocket message)                    |
| In Python before encode | `physics_pb2.TrackingStatus` instance              |

### Buffers and Queues

- **Node.js async generator queue:** In-memory, per-call. Bounded by SAM2 frame rate (~1 message per 200ms). Max queue depth: ~5 messages if WebSocket relay is slow. No overflow risk.
- **Python gRPC send buffer:** Managed by gRPC internals. Default flow control applies. No manual buffering required.

### Retained State

| What             | Where                                    | Lifetime         |
| ---------------- | ---------------------------------------- | ---------------- |
| gRPC channel     | Node.js module singleton                 | Process lifetime |
| Python executor  | `_executor` singleton                    | Process lifetime |
| Calibration JSON | `experiments/{id}/calibration/`          | Persistent       |
| Tracking JSON    | `experiments/{id}/results/tracks.json`   | Persistent       |
| Physics JSON     | `experiments/{id}/results/momentum.json` | Persistent       |

### Discarded State

- Individual SAM2 intermediate tensors (freed after each frame by PyTorch autograd)
- Raw `CalibrationStatus` / `TrackingStatus` messages: Node.js does not persist these; only the final `tracks.json` and `momentum.json` are durable.

